<b>Panzanella</b> or <b>panmolle</b> is a type of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../620/3735620.xml">
Italian dish</link> originating in the <subdivision wordnetid="108674251" confidence="0.8">
<region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<location wordnetid="100027167" confidence="0.8">
<tract wordnetid="108673395" confidence="0.8">
<geographical_area wordnetid="108574314" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../250/221250.xml">
regions</link></geographical_area>
</tract>
</location>
</region>
</subdivision>
 of <region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../734/30734.xml">
Tuscany</link></region>
, <region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../590/51590.xml">
Umbria</link></region>
, <region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../292/301292.xml">
Marche</link></region>
 and <region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../701/18701.xml">
Lazio</link></region>
. The dish is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/36969.xml">
bread</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../950/61950.xml">
salad</link> popular in the summer months. It includes sliced bread and fresh <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../234/9940234.xml">
tomato</link>es, flavored with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../865/346865.xml">
basil</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../478/22478.xml">
olive oil</link>, and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../762/32762.xml">
vinegar</link>, often with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../200/1605200.xml">
salt</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../116/150116.xml">
pepper</link>. The bread used should be day to week old saltless Tuscan bread made in a wood oven.<p>

Sometimes thought of as a "leftover salad," additional panzanella ingredients often vary widely, and could include <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../079/57079.xml">
lettuce</link>, <link>
white wine</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../317/309317.xml">
caper</link>s, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../741/234741.xml">
anchovies</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../535/6535.xml">
celery</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../739/5985739.xml">
carrot</link>s, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../961/32961.xml">
red wine</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../808/4955808.xml">
red onion</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../491/164491.xml">
cucumber</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../211/46211.xml">
tuna</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../206/23206.xml">
parsley</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/3719867.xml">
boiled eggs</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../955/18955.xml">
mint</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../940/71940.xml">
bell pepper</link>s, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../288/214288.xml">
lemon juice</link>, and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../469/50469.xml">
garlic</link>.</p>


